--------------------
----->Sniffing<-----
--------------------
Sniffing occurs at Layer 2 of OSI Model
Active - Switch-Based
Passive - Hub-Based

//Countermeasures
1. Static IP-Addresses
2. ARP Static Addresses
3. Encrypted Sessions (SSH vs. Telnet)
4. SCP vs. FTP
5. SSL

//Type of Attack
1. ARP Poisoning
2. MAC Attack
3. DHCP Attack
4. Spoofing
5. DNS Poisoning

//Sniffing Information Obtained
1. Syslog Traffic
2. Telnet Password
3. Router Configurations
4. FTP Passwords
5. DNS Traffic
6. Email Traffic
7. Web Traffic
8. Chat Sessions

//Steps Involved
1. MAC Flood (Yersinia, MACof)
2. DHCP Starvation (DHCPstarv, Gobbler)
3. Perform Rogue Server Attack
4. Perform ARP Poisoning Attack (Cain & Able, WinARPAttacker, Ufasoft snif)
5. Perform MAC Spoofing (sMAC)
6. Perform IRDP Spoofing
7. Perform DNS Spoofing (ARPspoof, DNSspoof)
8. Perform Cache Poisoning
9. Perform Proxy Server DNS Poisoning

-----------------------------
----->Denial of Service<-----
-----------------------------
//DoS Preventative Measures
1. Disable un-necessary services
2. Anti-Malware
3. Router Throttling
4. Reverse Proxy
5. Ingress Egress Filtering
6. Degrading Services
7. Absorbing the attack

//Bot-Net Preventative Measures
1. RFC 3704 Filtering
2. Black Hole Filtering
3. Source IP Reputation Filtering

//Types of Attacks
1. Service Request
2. SYN Attack/Flood
3. ICMP Flood
4. Ping of Death
5. Teardrop
6. Smurf
7. Fraggle
8. Land
9. Permanent 
10. Application-level Attack

//Dangerous Functions
gets()
strcpy()
scanf()
strcat()

//ICMP Attacks
1. Ping of Death - Fragmented attacks that cause a buffer over-flow
2. SYN Flood - Large amount of TCP SYN segments sent
3. SMURF - Spoofed IP address flood with Echo Reply 
4. ICMP Flood - Large amount of ICMP packets sent a target to saturate host


NOP = 0x99
